"asia","counts":[null,null,null,null,null,null,null,5032,21500,40419,68263,76493,78976,64154]},{"id":"korea","name":"Korea","region":"asia","counts":[null,null,null,null,null,null,null,2665,20380,56949,70990,72822,53468,54889]},{"id":"bangladesh","name":"Bangladesh","region":"asia","counts":[null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,1280,8695,42865,74692,99472,110793]},{"id":"philippines","name":"Philippines","region":"asia","counts":[null,null,null,null,null,null,null,8275,21260,36463,49644,50925,57191,51927]},{"id":"pakistan","name":"Pakistan","region":"asia","counts":[null,null,null,null,null,null,null,932,4440,14911,39165,39794,36804,34212]}],"note":"Immigrant waves by country of birth. 1900 and 1910 from the 1910 U.S. Census (Table 29, New York city). 1920 and 1930 from the 1930 U.S. Census (Vol. II, Table 9, New York, N.Y.). 1970-2000 and 2011 from NYC Dept. of City Planning, Newest New Yorkers 2013, Table 2-3 (the 2011 ACS figure is shown in the 2010 column). 2020 from the U.S. Census Bureau American Community Survey 2022 5-year estimates, table B05006, New York city. 2023 from NYC Dept. of City Planning, The Newest New Yorkers 2026, Chapter 2 (top-20 foreign-born groups, based on the 2023 ACS); groups outside that report's top 20 (Germany, Ireland, Austria, Hungary, Poland, Romania, Greece, Sweden, Cuba) are from the 2023 ACS 1-year B05006, summed across the five boroughs. China combines the mainland, Hong Kong and Taiwan to match the City Planning definition. Czechoslovakia is no longer an ACS birthplace category, so its 2023 cell is blank and the bar ebbs to zero. 1940, 1950 and 1960 are not filled from primary sources, so those cells are blank and the bars interpolate across them.","caution":["Bars show foreign-born New Yorkers only: the immigrant (first) generation, counted by country of birth. US-born children and grandchildren are not in these numbers.","The fade is a visual encoding, not a measured generation count: once a country is past its peak foreign-born decade, its bar dims in proportion to how far it has fallen from that peak. It marks a wave receding into its American-born later generations, whom the census cannot track by nation.","Country borders changed, and the census recorded birthplace as the state that existed at the time. The 'Russian Empire / U.S.S.R.' bar is one continuous series spanning the Russian Empire, the Soviet Union and present-day Russia. Before about 1920 the census counted everyone born in this territory as 'Russia,' and the overwhelming majority of these New Yorkers were Jewish emigrants from the Pale of Settlement -- land that is now Ukraine, Belarus, Lithuania, eastern Poland and Moldova -- not ethnic Russians; Ukraine breaks out separately only from 2000. Likewise, Poland did not exist as a census birthplace before 1920 (Poles were split among Russia, Austria and Germany), so its bar enters in 1920; and the Austria bar in 1900-1910 is really Austria-Hungary (Czechs, Slovaks, Poles, Croats and others). The Austria and Hungary counts for 1920 were disrupted by the empire's break-up. Czechoslovakia enters in 1920 and is dropped after 2010 (it dissolved). 'United Kingdom' uses England-born figures for 1900-1930 and the full UK from 1970.","Sources: 1900-1930 from U.S. Census decennial volumes; 1970-2011 from NYC City Planning; 2020 from the Census ACS 2022 5-year estimates. 1940-1960 are interpolated and labeled as such. Figures between censuses are interpolated and are exact only at each decade. The 1930 city total derived here (2,358,686) matches the published census total."]}}